HEADINGS
<h1-h6> - heading sizes

PARAGRAPHS
<p> - paragraph
<br> - line break
<pre> - Preformatted text
<hr> - horizontal rule

FORMATTING
<b> - Bold text
<strong> - Important text
<i> - Italic text
<em> - Emphasized text
<mark> - Marked text
<small> - Smaller text
<del> - Deleted text
<ins> - Inserted text
<sub> - Subscript text
<sup> - Superscript text
<del> - strikethrough text

LINKS
<a href="https://www.w3schools.com">Visit W3Schools.com!</a> - link
<a href="html_images.asp" style="text-decoration:none;">HTML Images</a> - 'text-decoration' removes underline eg on link
<a href="html_images.asp" target="_blank">HTML Images</a> - 'target' makes link opens in different place; blank is in a new window
<a href="default.html"><img src="smiley.gif"></a> - makes the image become a link
<a href="mailto:someone@example.com">Send email</a> - link to an email address
<button onclick="document.location='default.asp'">HTML Tutorial</button> - link on a button
<a href="default.html" title="Home">Back to Home</a> - 'title' allows tooltip, in this case "Home"

The 'target' attribute displays where the response to form submission gores and can have one of the following values:

_self - Default. Opens the document in the same window/tab as it was clicked
_blank - Opens the document in a new window or tab
_parent - Opens the document in the parent frame
_top - Opens the document in the full body of the window

Use the <a> element to define a link
Use the href attribute to define the link address
Use the target attribute to define where to open the linked document
Use the <img> element (inside <a>) to use an image as a link
Use the mailto: scheme inside the href attribute to create a link that opens the user's email program

FORMS
<input type="text">	- Displays a single-line text input field
<input type="radio">	- Displays a radio button (for selecting one of many choices)
<input type="checkbox">	- Displays a checkbox (for selecting zero or more of many choices)
<input type="submit">	- Displays a submit button (for submitting the form)
<input type="button">	- Displays a clickable button

<form>
  <label for="fname">First name:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname"><br>
  <label for="lname">Last name:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname">
</form>
 - displays 2 empty text boxes with titles

<form><input type="button" value="OK"></form> - input method is button with 'Ok' as value

<form>
<input type="radio" name="fav_language" value="html">HTML
<input type="radio" name="fav_language" value="css">CSS
</form>
 - displays 2 radio buttons with titles

FORM ATTRIBUTES
<form action="/action_page.php">Name: <input type="text" name="name"><input type="submit">
</form>
 - Titled text box with submit button

Form-data can be sent as URL variables (with method="get") or as HTTP post transaction (with method="post"). The default HTTP method when submitting form data is GET

<form action="/action_page.php" method="post">Name: <input type="text" name="name"><input type="submit">
</form>

